    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-12-20T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-12-20T04:00:00-05:00" n="554"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d554">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/12–2048: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-12-20T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 20, 1948—5 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 21—8:58 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2587. Resolution introduced in Legislative Yuan December 7 that China’s case be
                    brought before United Nations is stalled in committee and early action appears
                    unlikely. Opposition to bill in Legislative Yuan based on difficulty of proving
                    Soviet complicity and feeling that in any case UN powerless to help.</p>
                <p>Only about 300 legislators remain Nanking. Yuan’s activities, now confined
                    largely to discussing plight of nation, interpellating officials and passing
                    unimportant measures, are scantily reported in <pb facs="0677" n="667"
                        xml:id="pg_667"/> press. In anticipation of Sun Fo’s resignation,
                    Legislators have been actively promoting their candidates for President of Yuan,
                    with Wu Tieh-cheng and W. W. Yen most prominently mentioned. CC group has
                    reportedly thrown support to Yen after finding not enough votes could be
                    mustered to elect Chen Li-fu. Present Yuan session scheduled end December
                    28.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
